tion network"}, "mechanism": "Phosphate transfer to the serine hydroxyl creates an activated phosphorylated amino acid linked to proto-metabolic chemistry.", "reasoning": "Powner-group network studies linked glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde chemistry to phosphoserine and pyruvate, connecting amino-acid and protometabolic phosphate chemistry in a shared prebiotic network (Nature Chemistry, 2017, 9:310)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Biochemical serine decomposition to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal dehydration pathway under anoxic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Serine dehydrates through aminoacrylate-like intermediates and ultimately yields pyruvate as the dominant thermal decomposition product.", "reasoning": "Serine is thermally fragile, and dehydration to pyruvate is the dominant decomposition pathway according to kinetic and computational studies; this step is critical for network realism and links serine to central carbon chemistry (K\u00f6rner et al., 2021; Al-Kwradi et al., 2024; Sato et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Biochemical retro-aldol decomposition of serine to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-400K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal decomposition in anoxic solution"}, "mechanism": "Retro-aldol cleavage of serine releases formaldehyde together with glycine-equivalent carbon-nitrogen fragments; the formaldehyde product is explicitly tracked here.", "reasoning": "Retro-aldol decomposition to glycine plus formaldehyde is one of the three major serine destruction routes described in the literature; tracking formaldehyde closes the network back to sugar generation chemistry (K\u00f6rner et al., 2021; Qian